		<div class="comment_text"><p>The success of World of Warcraft has a great deal of attention as to why it is addictive.  The game presents an interesting method to catch the attention of its audience.  The presentation, delivery and content draw people of all ages. The information presented is neat, progressive and easy to navigate.</p><p>Now, imagine a progressive education system adopted the practices of MMORPGs or specifically World of Warcraft, delivery of information would be absorbed at rates that would astound you.  If you ask a World of Warcraft veteran, they could spout hours of information about the lore of the virtual realm.</p><p>Imagine an MMORPG that is based upon real history of the napoleonic war that has the stickness of World of Warcraft?  I bet you people would talk hours on end on the reasons why Napolean won and lost.</p><p>On the geek side of World of Warcraft, the UI is XMl based and has a scripting engine that allows you directly modify most of the interface through the use of LUA files.  So, if you enjoyed the MUD (Multi-User Dimension) aspect of coding, you can continue this trend, but cannot change the realm iteself as you could then.</p></div>
